WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.680
Today, I'm going to talk about how to make Shiny apps faster with caching using features

00:00:09.680 --> 00:00:13.280
from the new version of Shiny, version 1.6.

00:00:13.280 --> 00:00:16.959
Here's an app that shows average weather patterns over the course of a year.

00:00:16.959 --> 00:00:19.680
So let's take a look at the weather where I live in Minneapolis.

00:00:19.680 --> 00:00:24.799
We'll load the data, and the weather here is pretty typical for the continent of the

00:00:24.799 --> 00:00:25.799
United States.

00:00:25.799 --> 00:00:32.799
It's hot in the summer, cold in the winter, and it rains more in the summer and less in

00:00:32.799 --> 00:00:33.799
the winter.

00:00:33.799 --> 00:00:37.639
I have relatives that live in the Bay Area in California, and sometimes I compare my

00:00:37.639 --> 00:00:40.360
weather to theirs, and I feel a little sad.

00:00:40.360 --> 00:00:44.840
But then I compare real estate prices, and I feel a lot better.

00:00:44.840 --> 00:00:48.919
So here's the weather for Redwood City, California.

00:00:48.919 --> 00:00:51.480
In the summers, it's warm.

00:00:51.480 --> 00:00:55.919
In the winters, it's cooler, but it doesn't ever get really cold.

00:00:55.919 --> 00:01:00.520
And in the winters, it rains a lot.

00:01:00.520 --> 00:01:06.440
And in the summers, it rains almost not at all.

00:01:06.440 --> 00:01:10.160
Now with this app, there's a button that you can use to switch between the previous city

00:01:10.160 --> 00:01:11.279
and the current one.

00:01:11.279 --> 00:01:18.040
So you can switch to Minneapolis by clicking on there, and back to Redwood City by clicking

00:01:18.040 --> 00:01:19.040
on it again.

00:01:19.599 --> 00:01:24.360
But you notice that every time we do that, it has to re-go out and re-fetch the data

00:01:24.360 --> 00:01:26.480
and then redraw the plots, and that takes time.

00:01:26.480 --> 00:01:31.720
And so this experience of switching back and forth isn't really a great one.

00:01:31.720 --> 00:01:33.360
Now how can we make it better?

00:01:33.360 --> 00:01:37.720
Well, the answer is with caching.

00:01:37.720 --> 00:01:39.879
Here's some simplified code from the app.

00:01:39.879 --> 00:01:45.040
We have the weather data, which is a reactive expression, and that calls a function called

00:01:45.040 --> 00:01:49.040
fetchData, and you give that the city that you want to fetch the data for.

00:01:49.040 --> 00:01:52.279
And that goes out to the internet, it grabs the data, and then it returns.

00:01:52.279 --> 00:01:53.599
This takes a while.

00:01:53.599 --> 00:01:56.720
This is the slowest part of the application.

00:01:56.720 --> 00:02:01.879
In Shiny 1.6, we've added a function called bindCache.

00:02:01.879 --> 00:02:07.680
The way it works is you pass your reactive expression to the bindCache function, and

00:02:07.680 --> 00:02:10.279
then you tell it what to use as the cache key.

00:02:10.279 --> 00:02:13.000
In this case, it's input$city.

00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:18.199
So the first time you have a particular value of input$city, it will run the reactive expression

00:02:18.199 --> 00:02:20.600
and store the value in the cache.

00:02:20.600 --> 00:02:24.839
And then if you ever have that same value again, instead of having to recompute the

00:02:24.839 --> 00:02:30.000
reactive expression, it can just fetch the old value out of the cache.

00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:34.779
And in this case, that means we don't have to go to the internet to fetch the data.

00:02:34.779 --> 00:02:40.119
The other part of our app that takes significant time is the plot rendering with renderPlot.

00:02:40.199 --> 00:02:44.880
And as it turns out, you can use bindCache with renderPlot as well, so that the plots

00:02:44.880 --> 00:02:49.240
for a particular city, instead of having to be recomputed every time, they can be simply

00:02:49.240 --> 00:02:51.080
fetched from the cache.

00:02:51.080 --> 00:02:53.440
And this can really speed things up.

00:02:53.440 --> 00:02:58.279
Okay, let's look at our app again, but this time with caching.

00:02:58.279 --> 00:03:03.839
So all we did was add bindCache to the reactive expression and to the renderPlots.

00:03:03.839 --> 00:03:05.479
And that's it.

00:03:05.479 --> 00:03:10.679
Now when we look at these cities and switch back and forth between them, it's pretty much

00:03:10.679 --> 00:03:11.679
instantaneous.

00:03:11.679 --> 00:03:15.119
Because instead of having to fetch the data and recompute the plots, it just grabs the

00:03:15.119 --> 00:03:19.320
plots and the data right out of the cache, which is very, very fast.

00:03:19.320 --> 00:03:23.440
So we've seen bindCache used with reactive and with renderPlot.

00:03:23.440 --> 00:03:27.960
And I should mention that before Shiny 1.6, it was possible to use caching with plots

00:03:27.960 --> 00:03:31.440
by using the renderCachedPlot function.

00:03:31.440 --> 00:03:35.759
But that's now equivalent to using a renderPlot and bindCache.

00:03:35.759 --> 00:03:37.440
But it doesn't stop there.

00:03:37.440 --> 00:03:43.160
You can also use bindCache with other render functions like renderText.

00:03:43.160 --> 00:03:48.919
And it will even work with render functions that are not in Shiny itself, like renderPlotly

00:03:48.919 --> 00:03:50.699
from the plotly package.

00:03:50.699 --> 00:03:54.220
All you have to do is add bindCached to the end of it.

00:03:54.220 --> 00:04:00.679
If you've written one of these render functions, in most cases, it will just work with bindCache.

00:04:00.679 --> 00:04:04.639
But if not, typically the changes that you need to make are quite small, just a few lines

00:04:04.639 --> 00:04:05.639
of code.

00:04:05.639 --> 00:04:08.899
There are a few details you might be wondering about.

00:04:08.899 --> 00:04:10.899
So first is the size of the cache.

00:04:10.899 --> 00:04:14.580
The default size is 200 megabytes in memory.

00:04:14.580 --> 00:04:16.239
Now that size can be changed.

00:04:16.239 --> 00:04:20.519
And instead of using it in memory, the cache can also be stored on disk.

00:04:20.519 --> 00:04:21.839
Next the scope.

00:04:21.839 --> 00:04:27.279
The cache is shared across all user sessions of an application by default.

00:04:27.279 --> 00:04:30.920
And that means that if one person fetches a particular dataset or views a particular

00:04:30.920 --> 00:04:35.160
plot, then other users can benefit from that.

00:04:35.160 --> 00:04:39.279
But if that's a problem for your particular use case, then the cache can be scoped to

00:04:39.279 --> 00:04:42.000
just one session instead.

00:04:42.000 --> 00:04:43.920
Next the lifetime.

00:04:43.920 --> 00:04:48.679
A memory cache is discarded when the app exits or it restarts.

00:04:48.679 --> 00:04:53.239
But a disk-based cache can persist across app restarts and can even be shared across

00:04:53.760 --> 00:04:58.640
multiple simultaneous R processes serving up the same app, as you might do with Connect

00:04:58.640 --> 00:05:00.279
or Shiny Server Pro.

00:05:00.279 --> 00:05:04.600
Thanks for listening, and I hope that you find bindCache useful for speeding up and

00:05:04.600 --> 00:05:06.279
scaling up your Shiny applications.

